<HEADLINE> El Nino Expected Later This Year or Early Next Year: Experts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 18 (Xinhua) -- Chinese oceanographers today expect
climatic repercussions on global weather as El Nino is expected to
come sometime this year or the next.
</P>
<P>
Wang Fei, director of the Marine Environmental Protection
Department of the State Oceanic Administration, issued the warning
today at a press conference on this year's marine disaster
forecast.
</P>
<P>
The conclusion was made by Song Jiaxi and his colleagues with
the National Marine Environmental Forecasting Center in their
annual marine disaster forecast report, which was released today.
</P>
<P>
El Nino phenomenon, which comes at an interval of roughly four
years, refers to abnormal temperature rises in tropical waters
which normally leads to global anomalies in weather and climate.
</P>
<P>
El Nino was blamed for the heavy summer rains in China, causing
devastating floods in areas along the middle and lower reaches of
the Yangtze River and northwest China in 1998.  
</P>
